segments.text: This is Mary Lee Nolan in an interview with Mrs. Lupe Alemán.
What's her name?
Guadalupe Alemán, but Lupe, well, Grande is Guadalupe Alemán.
And for my father, González.
González.
Yes.
Lupe González de Alemán.
Yes, for my husband.
Yes.
And where were you born?
I was born here in the Nueces County.
Yes.
Yes, I was born here, I was raised here.
In what year?
Well, I think I was 17, it seems.
And where was your father born?
My father, well, they are both from Mexico.
But I don't know where they are from.
No?
No.
But they invented a lot of... Nanahuato.
Nanahuato?
Yes.
Rial del Oro, Rial de Pozos.
I think they are neighbors like Tricorpos.
Yes.
And Robstown.
And that's what I heard them talking about.
Yes.
And I was born...
I was the first girl, I think, in their family.
Because I grew up in a place where they worked all day.
They worked.
My father, my grandparents, they worked all those lands because it was just a mountain.
And they dug a lot with talaches and with that they kept us, all of us, they kept digging, digging and de-rooting.
Todos mis tios, mis abuelitos, mi papá,
And my brother, the one I have there, I have a brother who lives there in the corner.
And that brother helped my father because he was the oldest.
But they were born in Mexico, the two of them.
They just came here, they were raised here.
And he was the oldest and he helped my father.
To grab the talacha, to dig very hard.
He worked very hard, my little brother and my father, to raise the others.
Well, and then that I know from those times that I grew up, that I was knowing, I still recognized all that.
I went to where my father worked.
I looked at them as they worked very hard.
And then I looked at many fields and many people.

their clothes hanging on the branches, their, this, grinding, making tortillas, some big firewood, there they put a comal like this, they were throwing tortillas, tortillas, and making their food, well.
I met a lot of friends like that.
So, I would look at what my grandpa was doing.
What is grandpa doing?
He would say, I am making, they were called, those were called galemes.
Galemes?
Galemes, from pure land.
From pure land, they made from firewood, from the inside, from pure firewood.
And then,
They would put them like this.
Then they would put grass on the firewood.
Then they would put a lot of dirt on top of everything.
They would cover it with dirt.
That whole pile of dirt.
But the firewood would stay inside.
And then there would be a hole in the firewood.
And they would put a lot of firewood in there.
And a lot of garbage so that a lot of firewood would be made.
That would burn.
It would burn.
After it burned, I think it lasted, I don't know much, but it seemed to last three days or a week to cook.
It was coal, like the one they make now.
Well, then, after it was ready, he was paying, paying, and he was getting smaller and smaller.
So, with a rake, they were doing it.
And they did it, and they did it, and they dug around it, and they were stretching it with that rake when it was already turned off.
So, here they had it very clean, and they were making all that coal like this, it had already been done, they did it like this, like this, all around they dug it with that rake.
That coal, there were many ribbons, you know what ribbons are.
Well, then they threw all that coal, they picked it like a potato.
They picked that coal, they ribbons, the ribbons like that.
They carried 30, 40 ribbons of that, of pure coal.
The town was very small, the town was very small.
What was this town called?
This little town?
Yes.
Well, from what I know, I don't know, but I never knew, since I knew what it was called, it was Corpos, because they took it to Corpos, when there were very few shops.
My grandpa took it to a huayín and there were no mules, because those, I think, cost more.
He had some
burritos, sí, sí, y él llevaba todos esos costalitos en eso y los llevaba a corpos.
Entonces mi abuelito no quería, mi abuelito no quería hablar, él le daba vergüenza, pero mi abuelita sí iba con él.
Mi abuelita era una señora muy delgadita,
She was a very pretty lady, but she was dark-skinned.
But she had a very pretty body.
She would go out on the street and say, Do you buy coal?
Yes, the ladies would come out.
Good morning.
Good morning.
This is my mother.
Nice to meet you.
Oh, here.
Here, here.
And then she tells me, well...
So, when she talked about all that, the ladies and gentlemen would go out to buy my grandparents.
I don't know if at that time it would cost about 15 cents, I think a dime.
They were very happy.
So with that, they bought everything they needed for food.
They bought everything they needed from the food, they came very delighted to the house because they brought a lot of food, of what they wanted with that.
Well, they followed them around, around with that.
Well, following until they finished that, but they always continued to dig, to dig, because they were paid money for that.
An acre, half an acre, they paid for it.
A fourth, an eighth, they said, that's what they paid for, what they did.
A little, but they paid for it.
Well, then, that was over and Desenray continued.
My father, then, he gathered money, he gathered money.
That was what my grandfather, my father, did.
They gathered money, so I think they met with the first boss that I knew, that I thought, that I thought that my father had that boss.
It was Mr. Yondón.
Yondón.
Yondón.
Yondón.
Uh-huh.
His name was Juan Yondón.
Yes.
Yes.
By the way, they live around the 9th before they reach Corpus.
They don't exist anymore, but I think one or two of his daughters do exist.
Yes.
His place is still there, because it was a very beautiful place.
I remember he was a fat man.
very pink, with a white beard, and he wore a big hat, and he was a very respectful man.
But he was a man, like his family, who was also very kind to Mexicans, because he wasn't Mexican.
But he was very kind to everyone.
Where was he from?
What part?
Well, I didn't know what part he was from because when I thought about it, it was that he lived there, he had all his property.
I think, who knows, he was the first founder of here because he had a very beautiful house.
It was worth a lot of money because the house still exists.
Well, my father worked with him for many years.
Then my father worked with a man, his name was Jose Han.
He was another boss of my father.
That boss was a very good boss with my father.
At that time, my father was no longer working at St. Ray's.
That was pure land.
They helped my father.
So they helped my father because we were already a lot, because we were 12 in the family.
12 in the family.
12 children?
Yes, 12.
This is your mother, correct?
Yes, she is my mother.
Your mother is Mrs. Juanita Gonzalez?
Yes.
Correct.
And you had 12 children?
Yes, you know it was in 19.
I almost had an abortion, but in 12.
God gave me so many families.
Maybe it's possible for your mother to tell me something about Mexico.
Well, yes.
Where were you born?
Well, I wasn't born in Rosario, because before they didn't tell their parents anything.
I didn't want anyone to talk to Recio because it would upset him.
I didn't know where I was born.
No?
I didn't know.
But you were born in Mexico.
Yes, I'm from Mexico.
In Mexico.
Where in Mexico?
I'm from Mexico, in Guanajuato.
Guanajuato?
Yes.
In what town or ranch?
Well, I almost grew up in a ranch.
A ranch?
A pure ranch, yes.
What's the name of this ranch?
Well, the ranch where my father used to work, well, sometimes there was no work here in the mines, and we would go to the ranch, because we created a mineral in the Real de Pozo.
Oh, yes.
Yes.
We grew up there, and when my father stopped working, he would take us to the ranch.
We had already worked for two or three weeks, and we came back from Vuelta a Rodar.
It's a well.
It's a well where they make the money from the mines.
It's on the side of San Luis Potosí.
It's on the side of San Luis Potosí.
Yes, it's very close to San Luis Potosí.
And your father was working with mines and also with the fields?
Yes, also with the fields, yes.
When he was tired of working with the mines, we would go to the fields to work.
One month, one week.
And in what year were you born, more or less?
Well, how old were you?
More or less.
When we were going there, my dad took me.
You?
What was your age?
No, mom doesn't know right now, nor do I know.
You were 90 years old.
More or less.
And when did your family come to Texas?
Oh, when we came to give here, my little boys came every half year.
Before 1910 or after?
Well, for what reason did you come to Texas?
Because you know that for Mexico there are a lot of needs.
Yes.
A lot of work, it's very cheap.
Yes.
And here, since our families were here, they fixed it and they took us.
Yes.
Yes, that's why we came here.
Yes.
And was there a war in Mexico these days?
We didn't know about that war, we were already here.
Wasn't there a war in Mexico?
That war that was in Mexico, we were already here when we knew about that war.
They were here when they were already here.
They were already here when they were already here.
They were very sad this war.
Yes, very sad.
They were talking about how sad it was.
We were already here.
Yes, I was very young.
Did you have a family here before you came?
No.
Is there a family here in Texas?
This was the first one.
Ah, yes, the first girl.
La primera tejana de la familia.
Sí.
De la familia.
Bueno.
Sí.
Tu historia.
Continuar.
Bueno, este, no sé ni dónde iba.
I went with the man who was my father's boss.
Yes.
Well, after that, those men helped my father a lot.
And they started to give him work.
And my brothers, we all started to grow.
So they, I don't know, they gave him...
about two, three, I don't know, about five acres of land.
So, the boss, Mr. Jose Han, he had, he was a man who had money, a man who had many mules, horses, quite a lot.
So,
We started helping my father because we were the three oldest.
And my father, that was everything.
Everything he gave us.
So my father, he helped him and bought mules for my father.
He bought a mule for my dad and he bought the first thing we worked with.
So my dad bought a cow for that man because the cow was very cheap because dad had a family and he was a very good worker and he was a very good dad.
Entonces, él le vendió esa vaca.
Esa vaca era muy buena y daba mucha leche.
Entonces, él sembraba mucho.
Mi papá, él lo ayudó con mulas.
Y yo no sé si las pagaría mi papá al contado o no sé, pero él lo ayudó con mulas.
Y mi papá, a veces que le pasaba una mula bronca y mi papá la amansaba.
Y él trató de comprarse luego luego con su trabajo un guayín, un tiro de mulas nuevas, porque él no le gustaba, le gustaba que trabajaran las mulas pronto.
Y luego entonces, en ese rancho que le dio esos cinco acres, no tenía mi papá, no había casa.
No, no había casa, nomás era el puro lugar.
Do you know what the house was like?
It was a very big tree, a very beautiful tree.
It was very big, like this, that tree that grew there in the corner of Salabor.
So my father, I don't know, he bought sheets, what do you call it?
Sheet.
Do you know what a sheet is?
Well, so he bought it.
So my father built a house.
The kitchen was big, he made the house like that.
So, I remember, we all went, we all took, we all went to that place, but there was no house.
But as it were, there was this tree.
And then, well, my father was very good, but
Entonces, mi papá, yo agarré una cobija.
¿Ves?
Yo no estaba muy grande, pero...
I grabbed a blanket and I tied it on the floor.
My father didn't like that I tied that blanket on the floor.
He grabbed one of those sticks that hit the mules.
I tried to run so they wouldn't hit me because I was sitting on the blanket, but he didn't like that.
He said to my father, I'm going to run, and my father did this and I fell.
Well, then when I fell down, he told me, you shouldn't have run, he said.
Well, I was going to tell you not to throw that mattress on the ground.
It was all I remember that my father was going to hit me.
Because my father never cursed us, nor did he ever do us wrong for him.
He built that house, and then we would step on it.
We would step on the cotton, corn, whatever it was.
And he would plant a lot of garden all the time.
So he would make us work.
There was a lot of harvest, a lot of cotton, because the water would come and the cotton would grow a lot.
So he would say,
They would grab the plow and we would work here.
They would grab the plow, all of us.
There was a lot of grass.
He would help us and guide us and give us encouragement and everything.
Well, I grew up with cotton.
My father used to sell cotton bags.
I don't know if that man was the fourth, or the middle, or I don't know how he did with his boss.
But then, my father always bought the best.
With what God gave him, he bought skulls,
all kinds of tools that he needed to work, he would buy them.
He thought about all that because he looked and because his boss told him.
And he always thought about having them for us.
Well, then...
The owner had a lot of food for the cows because he had a dairy farm.
He had silos that were very big and they fed them there.
So you would see a lot of guayines all loaded with pasture.
And that pasture was carried by the Guayines.
They were paid for that pasture, because they carried all that pasture to the machine.
He had a machine that you put the manhojo there, they were pure manhojos.
They cut it in the work and then they put it in the barn.
You see, they were in the barn.
He put workers to make the barn, like the Indians, that's how they did it.

Well, then, here were some loaders, the guayines arrived, like trunks, and they threw those loaders, they threw the pasture, the guayines, and they put them so high, so high, that's how they carried the guayines, all out of order, to the silos, to the machine.
Then, there, the guayine was like this, throwing all that manure there, and the machine was stirring it, and throwing it into that boat.
I think my father was paid, I'm not very sure because he didn't tell us, but I think he was paid like 5 or 10 pesos a day on each trip.
On each trip he was paid.
So he was earning his money and it was less for him.
They ran the guayines in a row, like trunks.
The first one to arrive would be the one to be loaded first, and the other one would make more trips.
Well, then my father with that guayín maintained the house much better.
But between the family and my mother, she...
and she would tell my father to buy what he needed all the time.
She didn't want good clothes, she didn't want anything good, like now.
She wanted my father to have what he needed to work.
That's what she said too.
So, he, my father, for a long time, he changed from there.
And then she gave it to me because I think time was over.
So my grandparents, they were always with my father, who are her parents.
Yes, they were always with my father.
So we went somewhere else, always to Don Juan Yondon's ranch.
And it was a house.
So it was a house.
So it was a house that they called the house of three waters.
Because it had three corridors.
One like this, another like this, another like this, and another like this.
And it was a round house.
Ah, how beautiful.
Yes, there were many rooms.
Well, the house was very big and everything, but there was no opportunity to make it nice inside.
One put what one could and what one had.
It had many windows and everything.
Well, there we spent the time, another more time, that all my friends still have
Las amigas de los meras amigas de mi papá, de mi mamá.
Ya quedaron nomás los hijos de ellos.
Entonces, este, se vino el chubasco.
Yo no sé en qué año fue ese chubasco muy grande que acabó Corpus.
Ajá.
Yes, ma'am.
yes yes well then I think I would have like some ten years I think what happened during this chubasco is chubasco the same thing as a hurricane
Well, I think so, like Celia, almost like that.
Because look, we were in that house, that house was very strong.
Well, there were my grandparents, there was a brother of mine who is the eldest in the family, my brother was 30 years old.
He didn't get married until he was 30 years old.
He got married after I got married.
Yes.
Well, then, there was all that Gallardo family.
They came to the strength of the Higronazo because the house of God was like this.
The water was given to him like this.
That family was given to him like this.
Because of his... Because of the water.
Yes, his body.
His body.
The water rose up to here.
In the middle of his body.
Yes, the water.
And they went, they were all tied together and held in their hands, and the air in their strength and the water, and they left with us, all that family.
So, there were my grandparents, there was that family, they were two, it was a son and his...
and his father, men, my father and my three brothers and my father and my three brothers, well, and those were five.
So they went inside quickly because the air didn't let them in.
So the air came like this, right?
It lifted the door, it sold it hard.
So they all grabbed a machete and they all ran to the side of the door.
There was a time when they locked her up.
There were five of them.
They locked her up, tied her up with a rope, and then they put something strong on her.
So the house was like this, but the house never fell.
And since they put pressure on her, that's where the hurricane came in, but it didn't come in.
Well, everything calmed down.
Everything calmed down and the water stayed.
So many people came from other places because they wanted help to help raise the river.
Because it was destroyed.
They looked at us.
Do you know where the river is?
That river over there, the 9th?
Yes.
Well, that river...
Había muchos árboles y todo.
No se miraban árboles.
Todo se miraba así, pero mirabas tú como un pueblo porque todo de otras partes se trajo a la agua.
Sí.
Todo.
Había...
Había cosas de aranzas, de tab, había de corpos, había de pueblos vecinos.
Todo había en ese río.
Todo había allí.
Una negrita la sacaron de un tanque de aceite.
Una señora la hallaron colgada en uno de los árboles.
Oh, my dad went to help.
My dad and that Gallardo family, the two of them went to help.
My brothers went to help because the boss told my dad, come on, help, he said, because they need help to lift up the debris that there was from the chubasco.
And all the neighbors from there left.
They came from many places to help there.
But you looked at it as if it had been a town.
You looked at how many things there were there.
So the police were taking care of it because there were many things of value thrown away.
And then they checked them all, those who were going to help them checked them.
They didn't bring anything.
But I'm not saying that I'm in favor of my parents or anything.
But my parents taught us to respect others.
And they respected me because I never told them to bring anything to the house.
From what was there, no.
I never saw anything.
I never knew anything because they never brought anything.
Well, then, after a short time, all of that, for a long time, they kept raising all of that.
After a short time, we left from there.
We all left for that ranch that still exists, but the owners don't.
Here it is, it was Jose Yaliva.
After that, from that ranch,
We went to... what is the 9th street?
It's the 9th street and we were there.
Do you know where the 9th street is?
37, number 37.
Hey Virginia, is the 9th street, what number is it?
It's the 9th street.
That's how we named it.
That's how we named it.
That's how we named it.
That's how we named it.
That's how we named it.
That's how we named it.
Yes, but she was Italian.
Yes, she was Italian.
Her wife was Mexican.
She was a very beautiful lady.
And they were very nice.
So they had a house because they were the first founders of Corpus.
So my father and they went to that place because that man told him,
Gonzales, I don't know how they would fix it, but he said he would pass his land to him so he could plant it.

Like my father, he already had everything, so he said, well, but I don't have a house, he said, but I have a little house, and that little house only had a room, as long as here, and the kitchen was divided, and it was small.
He said, there you go, he said, in the meantime, he said, but it's very good land, and it's enough.
So he said, my dad, it's good.
And so we went to that place.
So it was on the other side of that place, there was another land, and it was from another Italian.
Yes.
Yes, they were...
The only friends of the other Italians were friends.
So they had a very nice house because those families were the first ones.
They had a two-story house that still exists.
It was a two-story house, so my father was very close to them.
They were very close since my father came here and met all of that family.
They had their parents from those Italians.
They were very young, both of them.
My father and mother were this size.
Both of them were old.
But they didn't know any Spanish, but they were always good.
And my father had a very good friendship with them.
When my father needed something,
He would go with him.
When my father needed to borrow money, the man, that cigarette, would lend money to my father until the year was over.
When the year was over, with what my father raised, he would pay 200, 300 pesos to that man, with what my father raised, to live with us.
Bueno, entonces cuando él tenía trabajo, mi papá,
He was going to work with him.
When he didn't have money, he was going to work with him.
He helped him a lot.
My father really liked to play in the barrage.
They really liked to play in the barrage, the Italians.
They looked for my father.
My father, the day he didn't work, he was up until one in the morning, at four, with them, playing in the barrage.
They had a very good time with them.
He was...
They were two brothers, they were Italians.
They loved my father very much.
Well, then, they helped us all the time.
If he said,
Hey, Fernando, are you going?
Because my father's name was Fernando.
So he said, I want you to lend me a boy so that I can roll the cotton or whatever.
So my father says, well, you know, the boys are busy here, but if you want, my girl is going to help you.
Oh, that's good, Fernando.
We make the roll and all that.
Well, I was going to roll the work that they wanted, I was going to do it.
Well, then he had two girls, that man had, his name was Juan, the other one was called Rocky and the other one was called Juan.
So my father treated the older one, who was Juan.
Well, then he says he had,
Three girls.
And those girls, they were average, those girls.
Only one of them was the oldest.
So, they grew up, well, not much, but they were always big, the oldest.
Because they didn't let me, like now, they didn't let me play a lot.
They only gave me a certain amount of time to play with my friends.
That was one friend.
My cousin was another friend because my aunt lived next door to those Italians.
Y mi prima, pues casi era de la camada mía, pues tendría yo creo como algunos once o doce años, nosotros las tres.
At that time, the girl was Italian.
She had long hair and a beautiful family braid.
I went to my mother and asked her, Lupita, will your mother let you come to my house?
I said, I don't think so, because I'm working.
She said, I'm going to tell your mom.
And she came early.
And she said, Mrs. Juanita, let Lupita go play with me for a little while.
And Trinda, my cousin, said, well, she said, mom, well, go.
She said, but just for a little while, Lupe.
Half an hour.
or Asina.
We used to go and play together.
I used to play with the other cousin for a little while, either at her house or at my house.
For a little while, and then we'd go home.
Lupita would say, well, I'm leaving.
I'd go home soon.
But it wasn't all the time.
It was only once a week.
Or on Sundays, I'd do everything I could, and I'd have it on Sundays, but it was at my house, and my friends would go there.
to play with me, because I really liked the ball game.
And I still like the ball game.
And then, well, she begged a lot, that year that we were there, she begged a lot, my little friend, my mom and my dad, because my dad was in charge.
Entonces dice, ¿por qué no la dejan ir a Lupita que vaya a la escuela?
Yo nunca he ido a la escuela.
Nunca.
Why not?
Because the schools were retired.
They weren't very retired, but the parents were always stricter.
In short, the parents in those years didn't know what one could be missing.
Not even one could think of that.

Entonces, de allí estaba retirado, no estaba muy retirado, pero podíamos ir a pie como íbamos entonces, porque cuando esa amiguita me animó y a mi papá que me dejara ir, que me dejara ir a la escuela, entonces me dijo, pues está bueno que vaya a la escuela, dijo mi papá y mi mamá, pues que vaya a la escuela.
Pues que entonces ella estaba bien contenta porque allí no había amiguitas para que fueran de allí de ese barrio para que fueran con ella, nomás yo, mi prima y mi primo.
So, we went to the school.
That school was made by Mr. Jose Jante.
They told him.
He was my father's boss.
He made that school, which is on the way down.
I don't know if it will be closed.
On the way down, there is a school on the same road.
So we went to school and she had a lot of white friends, but she didn't leave us.
She always ran and talked with us.

Before leaving, she would go to the street and tell me, Lupita, because there was a mountain there, a little bit of a mountain, and she had my flip-flops, and I would get together with my cousin, and there weren't many Mexicans, so she would say, Lupita,
No te vayas a ir y me dejes sola.
Dice, Lupe, yo te doy un sándwich.
Dice, pa' que me esperes, me decía.
Le decía yo, pues dile a mi prima.
Le decía, si ella me espera a mí, entonces yo te espero a ti.
No necesito sándwich.
Entonces decía, ay, Lupita, por favor, dice, espérame.
So I said, well, and I said to my cousin, let's go, let's go, because she doesn't come with us when we're here, she doesn't come with us, she says, it's better to go.
Oh no, I said to her, let's wait, poor thing, let's wait.
Well, well, I'm not going to go, I'm going to wait for her.
Well, then we were waiting for her.
And she did go with us.
So when we were going, she was sharing sandwiches with us and my cousin always
Well, she didn't like it.
So she said, she said, oh, yes, she said, oh, don't lick me so much that I don't have a ranch.
She said, she said, my cousin, oh, cousin, why are you so bad?
I said, well, playing like that, well, then.
Ay, pues que mi primer maestra que ya murió, fue primera y última maestra que yo tuve, fue Miss Bessie.
Bueno, esa maestra fue una maestra que vino de otros estados, esa maestra.
